Climateworks is a team of researchers, strategists, collaborators, and grant-makers, with the goal of increasing philanthropic impact on climate change. The strategies have been defined in 2007 in the joint publication: Design to Win: Philanthropy’s Role in the Fight Against Global Warming, a report that identified priorities charted course for climate philanthropy. The Hewlett, Packard, and McKnight foundations — created ClimateWorks in 2008, with the commitment to seeing these strategies put into action. During the first 6 years CW made grants worldwide, helped build capacity and collaborated with a network of partners to support research, policy advocacy, outreach and public engagement, all with the aim of reducing the emissions that cause climate change. In 2013 CW took on a bigger role to help leading climate funders coordinate and to work with partners around the world to grow climate philanthropy and reduce the emissions. CV supports the international goal to prevent global average temperature increase from exceeding 2°C, to maximize the energy that comes from sustainable, affordable, low-carbon sources, putting an emphasis on effective public policy, business innovation, public support

The Center for the Study of Carbon Dioxide and Global Change was created to disseminate factual reports and commentary on new developments in the world-wide scientific quest to determine the climatic and biological consequences of the ongoing rise in the air's CO2 content. Weekly online publication: the CO2 Science magazine, which contains editorials on topics of current concern and mini-reviews of recently published peer-reviewed scientific journal articles, books, and other educational materials. In addition, the Center maintains on-line instructions on how to conduct CO2 enrichment and depletion experiments in its Global Change Laboratory, which allow interested parties to conduct similar studies in their own homes and classrooms. Specific projects and data: Medieval warm project period – Plants growth database – Ocean acidification database – World temperatures dataset

Founded in 1971 by economist Barbara Ward, who forged the concept and cause of sustainable development, IIED advises government, business and development agencies, arguing for changes in public policy. IIED carries out research, advice and advocacy work, focusing on bottom-up solutions, informed by practical perspective acquired through hands-on research with grassroots partners. IIED has four research groups. The Climate change group is working, in collaboration with partner organisations and individuals in developing countries, on adaptation to climate change issues. IIED contributes to international policy processes and frameworks including the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, the Millennium Ecosystem Assessment and the UN conventions on climate change and biological diversity

Global Landscapes Forums, held alongside the UN climate negotiations, create a platform for positioning landscapes in the new international agreements on climate and sustainable development. The landscapes approach allows stakeholders to identify policy options, investment opportunities and research priorities by: understanding how land-use choices in one area affect other areas, negotiating competing demands, assessing actors that affect land uses, studying how groups benefit differently from land uses, leveraging private and public capital for sustainable development in the landscape

The core tasks are: to investigate and document current environmental, ecological and spatial quality and to evaluate policy; to explore future social trends and possible policy options; to identify social issues of importance and identify possible strategic options for achieving government objectives in the field. The company specializes in expertise in energy saving, sustainable energy solutions and climate policies, with the purpose to help countries in designing policies in such a way that they bring economic benefits and reduced risks, to help opinion leaders develop new ideas for policy designs, and to help companies operate profitably in the policy landscape. Areas of expertise are : Energy and carbon efficiency, Renewable energy, Energy systems and markets, Energy and climate policy. actions not only address concerns about man-made climate change, but also deal with issues such as the rising cost of energy, security of energy supply and the need for sustainable development. Ecofys is heavily involved in shaping carbon markets

The Green Climate Fund was designated as an operating entity of the financial mechanism of the UNFCCC, to provide support to developing countries to limit or reduce their greenhouse gas emissions and to adapt to the impacts of climate change, taking into account the needs of those developing countries particularly vulnerable to the adverse effects of climate change. It will strive to maximize the impact of its funding for adaptation and mitigation, and seek a balance between the two, while promoting environmental, social, economic and development co-benefits and taking a gender-sensitive approach.

The website of the National oceanic and atmospheric administration (NOAA) of the US dept of commerce is hosting several websites : Weather.gov website forecast (national weather services ) - Climate.gov (science and information for a climate-smart nation, including a Global climate dashboard) - and Ready. gov (Prepare, Plan, Stay informed which focuses on risks and management of the climate emergency situations

Website of WWF’s Earth Hour, considered to be the world’s largest grassroots movement. Considers that while the global lights out remains an impactful visual call-out, its true impact is starting to be seen in areas and communities fighting climate change on an everyday basis. Web pages dedicated to the celebration of the Earth Hour around the world; list of environmental projects with the purpose of working for a living planet and sustainable living…

Climatism aims to draw attention to the "alarmism" and the lack of reliable arguments against it. Anonymous points of view to challenge the "alarmists" (Gore, Viner, Hansen) claims and the "human induced climate change narrative".

Consider that there is much evidence to suggest that temperature fluctuations are part of a natural cycle of climate change, and that the unproven “solutions” being proposed by global warming advocates would ultimately cost billions of dollars to implement. Readers are invited to “learn the truth” (list of “Must-see videos”) and then become actively involved in promoting “the cause of freedom” (“The ten things you can do”, including distribute GSM flyers, visit congressmen, write to papers, put GSM bumper sticker on car, make donations…)

Environment news section of the Guardian, with a sub-section on climate change. Among recent postings, an interview of Naomi Klein on climate change (I thought it best to write about my own raw terror) published on the 26th August 2015

Focusing on President Obama’s America’s Clean Power Plan, which sets the first-ever carbon pollution standards for power plants. The Clean Power Plan standards are designed to reduce carbon dioxide emissions by 32 percent from 2005 levels by 2030. By setting these goals and enabling states to create tailored plans to meet them, the Plan intends to: Protect the health of American families, Boost the economy by leading to 30 percent more renewable energy generation in 2030 , Save enough energy to power 30 million homes in 2030 and Save consumers $155 billion from 2020-2030

Blog d’un universitaire et chercheur anonyme, initialement créé sous le nom de WottsUpWithThatBlog, pour réfuter les affirmations de Anthony Watts, adepte de la théorie du « Climate gate » qui remet en cause sur son site Watts Up With That (WUWT) la validité des études, démonstrations et arguments des « alarmistes climatiques » particulièrement Al Gore. The IER is a not-for-profit organization that conducts research and analysis on the functions, operations, and government regulation of global energy markets. According to IER if we wish to ensure the adequate and reliable energy supply necessary for our economy and security, we need to ensure adequate supplies of fossil fuels for decades to come. IER maintains that freely-functioning energy markets provide the most efficient and effective solutions to today’s global energy and environmental challenges; that private property rights, market exchange, and the rule of law have resulted in affordable energy, improved living standards and a cleaner environment. To improve the public’s access to information about existing federal energy programs, IER compiled a comprehensive database, the Federal Energy Spending Tracker, that contains the most significant forms of federal subsidies for energy producers and energy products. The database covers all sources of energy across all government agencies

Blog of the Canadian investigative journalist Donna Laframboise, former vice president of the CCLA. Author of 2 books about the IPCC, she is described by Der Spiegel as the IPCC’s "sharpest critic". DL began by designing the NOconsensus.org website. This blog began as working notes for her 2011 book, and then morphed into an exposé of the IPCC. Argues that The IPCC is an "unprofessional, scandal-plagued organization, led by people with low standards and impaired judgment, and that we need to stop taking it seriously". Among the blog categories: Climate bible, Climategate, the last one including such links as : Global warming, loyalty oaths, and Climategate's smoking gun

The aims and objectives of Climate realists are to draw attention to the “real explanations” as to what has made the climate change and to voice an educated opinion against the “unscientific and unsubstantiated reasoning” behind green taxation. Climate Realists intends to actively promote the proposition that there is no such thing as Man Made Climate Change, and takes the view that climate change is something we have no control over and simply have to learn how to adapt

EPA was established on December 2, 1970 to consolidate in one agency a variety of federal research, monitoring, standard-setting and enforcement activities to ensure environmental protection. The Climate change website provides the American public in general with information about climate change: basic information, information on greenhouse gas emissions (sources of emissions, global data, national data, facility data, individual calculator), information on climate change science (causes and indicators of climate change, future climate change), information on climate change impacts and adaptating to change. Includes educator links and a student’s guide to Global climate change.

Photographic documentation of climate change, by Gary Braasch. The website was designed to “make the climate change visible”, Photographs are organized according to following subject matters: Antarctica – Arctic – Alaska – Unstable weather – Glaciers – Coastlines/Sealevels – Oceans and Tropics – Hawaii – Himalaya and Asia – South America – World Climate change. They are available for license to publications needing science photography, environmental groups and agencies, and other uses

Website of the Stop Global Warming Virtual March (1,467,783 supporters) non-political movement to demand world leaders freeze and reduce carbon dioxide emissions now. The first step of proposed action is to Join the Virtual March, The second step is to Keep reading and share with friends information provided by the website on Global Warming, environmental destruction, health risks, catastrophic weather

Global Warming is Real (GWIR) was founded in June of 2006 by Tom Schueneman, member of the Society of environmental journalists, and founder of TDS environmental media, who has studied climate and environmental issues and attended the COP15 climate conference in Copenhagen. The website is designed for the concerned citizen, as the go-to resource for news, commentary and education on all aspects of global warming. The Climate page offers comprehensive information on global warming (Global warming news – Climate science – Climate deniers – Habitats – Climate change and civil society – Climate change and human rights – Climate change and business – Climate change and politics – Climate change mitigation – Climate change podcast). Readers are invited to contribute (“join the conversation”, “reader’s pick). Also proposes a “Global climate reader” (recommended readings on climate change, energy, and sustainability) and Climate videos

AGW (Anthropogenic Global Warming) is about climate science with an emphasis on the observational side, and on the issues relating to the ongoing climate change. In the opinion of the author, the public discussion on the subject tends to focus more on what climate models can do instead of emphasizing the observational body of evidence which is very large and convincing by itself even without far-reaching climate theories or models (which is not to say that climate models are not important and useful tools). The blog is designed to offer relevant information on the subject : introduction to the Observations of Anthropogenic Global Warming, lists of papers (including list of anti-AGW papers debunked) the most popular being the list of “Papers on laboratory measurements of CO2 absorption properties”. Main categories: Adaptation & Mitigation - AGW evidence - Climate claims - Climate science - Global warming effects . Articles republished on : Skeptical Science - RealClimate

“We’re on the way to a cleaner, cleverer, low carbon world, and everyone deserves a chance to help build it. 10:10 creates these chances, and brings people together to make the most of them” 10:10 is about doing “practical stuff that helps solve climate change”. From riding a bus to repowering a village with solar energy, the projects “bring people together to help build a better world” ; focus is on renewables powered projects in France, UK, The Netherlands, Germany…

The blog is “about the insanity surrounding Anthropogenic Global Warming". Criticizes the “believers” on one side and the “deniers” on the other, insisting that what is going on, one way or the other, has to be based upon real science and not altered data, consensus, student papers, magazine articles, pure fantasy, BS, or on a human “deity.” the movies, documentaries, and videos presented here are embedded from other media source / host sites on the internet. The mission of “Climate Busters”, hosted by SouthWest Weather Inc., is defined as follows : Exposing the carbon dioxide global warming myth - Explaining the real causes for climate change - Exactly how we feel the climate will change - The economic ramifications of climate change. The Climate Busters intend to give their clients “the information they need to prepare and profit in relation to the coming climatic changes”. They favour a particular solar climate mechanism/connection theory according to which they ”expect global cooling to be quite substantial going forward”

The Climate Bonds Initiative is an international, investor-focused not-for-profit, focusing on mobilizing the $100 trillion bond market for climate change solutions. Climate Bond Partners get access to detailed data on bond issuance, market insights and opportunities to collaborate on events, government lobbying and investor education. CBI is now in Public Consultation for the latest version (V1.9) of the Climate Bonds Standard. The updated version (2.0) of the standard will enable the following features : More practical assurance framework - Updated Green Bond Principles - Explicit Annual reporting requirements - Accomodation of all the different types of bond

The European Climate Foundation (ECF) was established in early 2008 to promote climate and energy policies that reduce Europe’s greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions and to help Europe play an even stronger international leadership role to mitigate climate change. The ECF – a ‘foundation of foundations’ – is to collaborate in ensuring the necessary transformation from a high-carbon to a low-carbon economy. Emphasis is on four types of activities: Providing thought leadership that leads to new narratives - Creating a robust evidence base to underpin the case for change - Convening the right players - Creating awareness of the facts and the need for action

Climate Access is managed by a team of experts in environmental communications and research. The organization defines itself as “The network for those engaging the public in the transformation to low-carbon, resilient communities”, intending to provide the knowledge that network practitioners need to take their communications to the next level, by using proven techniques for mobilizing audiences to reduce emissions, prepare for impacts and support climate policies. Climate Access builds capacity through: Network , Research and analysis, Trainings and events. The “ResourceHub” is a collection of resources for essential research, news articles and commentary on climate change communications, behavior change and public opinion). The “CampaignGallery” is showing how individuals, communities and organizations are taking action to address climate change. Climateaccess members are able to discuss the campaigns with experts, submit campaign examples and discuss best outreach practices in the Member Forums. "Tips and Tools" for climate communicators feature expert recommendations in the form of user-friendly tip sheets, archives of Climate Access roundtable discussions

Climate Analytics was founded in 2008 to bring vanguard climate science and policy analysis to bear on human induced climate change, with the objective of empowering those most vulnerable to use the best science and analysis available in their efforts to secure a global agreement to limit global warming to levels that don’t threaten their very survival. CA brings together interdisciplinary expertise in : Science and impacts analysis – Climate impacts and risk assessment – Mitigation scenarios and pathways (greenhouse-gas emission reductions necessary to achieve long-term global climate goals, such as holding warming below 1.5 and 2°C warming relative to pre-industrial levels) – Negotiating support (on-demand advice to negotiators, with the aim of supporting the establishment of an effective and legally binding multilateral climate regime) – Climate negotiations (support to assist Small Island Developing States (SIDS) and Least Developed Countries (LDCs) in the UNFCCC, Green Climate Fund and related climate negotiations – Climate action tracker (An independent science-based assessment tracking all countries‘ emission reduction pledges and their implementation)

Within the framework of global negotiations on climate change, the UNDP and the World Bank Group have jointly developed the web-based knowledge platform, which a number of UN agencies and multilateral development banks (MDBs) use as a joint conduit of information on investment finance. It is also building an interactive community of practice to share South-South experience and best practices in climate action for better development impact.The Platform provides: A harmonised description of types of funds available - Examples of successful cases of blending different types of grant and concessional funds to leverage private sector financing, in addition to enabling environments conducive to climate action; all of which will be supplemented by examples provided by stakeholders through discussion forums of registered Platform users. - Knowledge centre with a glossary of terminology, a library , and tools to enable project developers to analyse their own projects for better-informed decisions - User community collaborative space for users to connect, share ideas, plan projects, and facilitate South-South networking

Group of private citizens, comprised mainly of active and retired earth and atmospheric scientists, geologists, geophysicists, engineers and other professionals, who declare themselves to be concerned about the apparent gross manipulation and falsification of scientific data that has occurred, in an effort to convince authorities that a problem exists, and especially concerned about the one-sided misinformation being fed to children in school, especially the Al Gore movie, which has been shown to contain a large number of false claims. Among the “myths” listed , and discarded, in the section « Myths and facts »: Global temperatures are rising at a rapid, unprecedented rate –The Earth has recently experienced a sudden increase in temperature Human produced carbon dioxide has increased over the last 100 years, adding to the Greenhouse effect, thus warming the earth – CO2 is a pollutant – The Earth’s poles are warming…

skeptics / The Heartland Institute is a 31-year-old national nonprofit organization devoted to discovering, developing, and promoting free-market solutions to social and economic problems. Heartland’s Center on Climate and Environmental Policy promotes pro-environment policies based on sound science and economics, not alarmism or ideology. The goal of the ICTSD, founded in 1996 in Geneva, is to advance sustainable development through trade related policy-making, through 3 types of activities: 1.: Information and communication (communications tools including 8 regularly published periodicals produced in 6 languages that cover region-specific issues) - 2: Policy dialogue (to create opportunities for dialogue and facilitate constructive interaction among policymakers and influencers in non-negotiating settings ) - 3: Research and analysis (ICTSD thus generates research and analysis that takes a solutions-focused approach to sustainable development in trade policy and related policy processes ). The Climate and energy subsection is dedicated to promoting the transition to a low carbon economy and a sustainable energy future, by providing: Latest news - Latest researches - Trending issues - Tweets

Climate Realists' Network was formed in July 2009 in New Zealand. The aims and objectives of Climate Realists are to draw attention to the “real explanations” as to what has made the climate change and to voice an "educated opinion" against the “unscientific and unsubstantiated reasoning” behind green taxation. Climate Realists intends to actively promote the proposition that there is no such thing as Man Made Climate Change, and takes the view that climate change is something we have no control over and simply have to learn how to adapt. The website contains a number of articles and links. The main form of communication is by way of fortnightly newsletters to members.

WRI engages businesses, policymakers and civil society at the local, national and international levels to advance transformative solutions that mitigate climate change and help communities adapt to its impacts. U.S. Climate Action Initiative identifies cost-effective solutions for the United States to reduce its emissions in the short- and long-term. CAIT 2.0 provides a platform for stakeholders to explore, understand and communicate climate and emissions data. The Greenhouse Gas Protocol helps companies and organizations measure, manage, and report their greenhouse gas emissions. Publications are subject to peer review

The Least Developed Countries are 48 nations that are especially vulnerable to climate change but have done the least to cause the problem. They work together at the intergovernmental negotiations under the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) to demand that wealthier nations act in accordance with their responsibility for creating the problem and their capability for addressing it. The UNFCCC website has a comprehensive collection of links to information that is of specific interest for LDCs, such as work on national adaptation programmes of action (NAPA), the work of the LDC Expert Group (LEG), the Least Developed Countries Fund (LDCF), relevant LDC decisions and Conclusions and frequently asked questions on NAPAs, the LEG and the LDCF. Countries pages and papers series

Introduction to the UNEP (United nations environment program) website on climate change. Insists that the most dangerous climate changes may still be avoided if we transform our hydrocarbon based energy systems and if we initiate rational and adequately financed adaptation programmes to forestall disasters and migrations at unprecedented scales. Website sections on : Science, Tools, Partners, Adaptation, Mitigation, REDD+ ...

DC was formed in 2007 with two core purposes: To syndicate quality journalism about climate change to other media outlets, and to provide a daily aggregation highlighting the best news on climate change from around the globe. The Daily Climate's aggregation represents the news of the day, irrespective of the opinion or viewpoint expressed, or whether or not material in the article is consistent with their understanding of current science. DC is working to increase public understanding of climate change. Subsections : Front Page - Newsroom (including index of the reporting - Solutions - Consequences - Causes - Politics - Energy - Coal - Extremes - UN talks - Science - Adaptation - Sea Level

The Copenhagen Consensus Center is a think tank is advising policy-makers and philanthropists how to spend their money most effectively on solving “the world biggest problems”. Among current projects, the Fix The Climate project , based on the consideration that Global warming is caused by man-made CO2 emissions, and we need to do something about it; to determine which response to global warming will be the best (to focus on adapting to living in a warmer world; to immediately regulate greenhouse gas emissions to minimize the causes of global warming; to place our faith in technological solutions like a large-scale manipulation of the planet’s atmosphere…) the CCC commissioned research papers from specialist climate economists, outlining the cost and benefits of each way to respond to global warming. This site presents the final result from the September 2009 expert meeting, the research papers, as well as personal stories from around the world on real people affected by global warming. Copenhagen Consensus on Climate culminated with the publication of Smart Solutions to Climate Change

According to the blog, started on 07/11/07 "Global warming" is hysterical alarm built on exaggeration and deceit, fuelled by those with a vested interest. List of links to skeptics websites and arguments against the warmists. The author is actively involved in various campaigns: to support the US governors who defy Obama climate rule - to support scrapping the Climate Change Act - to oppose Emission Trading - to endorse the Manhattan declaration on Climate Change (Climate Change is not a global crisis) - to try to keep Al Gore's "political propaganda film" out of English schools, etc

CRAIGM350 doesn’t believe anymore “the blatant fear mongering by the mainstream media and politicians” of the “CO2 possessed mythic powers”, even if he doesn’t agree with the skeptics dismissal of CO2 as being anything but a minor cause of the climate changes. Blog dedicated to the books published by B. Tisdale. BT was previously believing in the assumption that man is responsible for most of the recent global warming. His growing skepticism is motivated with his dissatisfaction with the ever increasing number of reports of projected climate catastrophes. He categorizes himself as “a lukewarmer - not a global warming denier” as he still understand the hypothesis of anthropogenic greenhouse gas-driven global warming, and still believe it has an impact on the warming of land surfaces, albeit a small one. 350.org a été fondé en 2008 aux Etats-Unis par un groupe d’universitaires et Bill McKibben, auteur d’un des premiers livres « grand public » sur le réchauffement climatique. Le chiffre fait référence à l’objectif de réduction de la quantité de CO2 dans l’atmosphère à moins de 350 ppm. 350.org vise la construction d’un mouvement climatique citoyen, à travers des campagnes "bottom-up" (désinvestissement des énergies fossiles notamment) menées par un réseau international présent dans plus de 188 pays. La mobilisation s’appuie sur les initiatives locales, l’organisation de journées internationales, les campagnes en ligne

The InterAcademy Council (IAC) is a multinational organization of science academies created to produce reports on scientific, technological, and health issues related to the great global challenges of our time (such as enhancing global surveillance of emerging infectious diseases; improving global water quality and availability; and scientific ethics and responsibilities) providing knowledge and advice to national governments and international organizations. On 10 March 2010, the UN and the IPCC Chairman requested IAC to undertake an independent review of the IPCC processes and the procedures by which it prepares its assessments of climate change. IAC is asked to establish a Committee of experts from relevant fields to conduct the review and to present recommendations on possible revisions of IPCC processes and procedures

Website of the transformational Climate Science conference, hosted by the University of Exeter in partnership with the Met Office and University of Leeds on 15 and 16 May, 2015. Climate change experts met in Exeter on 15 and 16 May to present and critically reflect on the IPCC’s Fifth Assessment Report (AR5). The report assesses scientific, technical, and socio-economic factors concerning climate change, its potential effects and the options for adaptation and mitigation. Conference participants included UK and international contributors to the IPCC report, who gave policy and scientific perspectives. Presentations from the event are now available, and videos will be available shortly

This website is the first chapter of a larger Greenpeace project to provide a research database of information on the corporate funded anti-environmental movement. The database compiles Exxon Foundation funding to a series of institutions who have worked to undermine solutions to global warming and climate change in recent years. Individuals working with these organizations and their global warming quotes and deeds are detailed. Interactive maps are designed to highlight the way in which individual opponents to the legislation on climate change in the US are connected with the corporate or institutional beneficiaries of funding. Downloadable source documents or links to sources are provided throughout

The U.S. Government Accountability Office (GAO) is an independent agency that works for Congress. Often called the "congressional watchdog," GAO investigates the Federal Governement expenses. The federal government’s efforts to respond to climate change include adaptation (adjustments to natural or human systems in response to actual or expected climate change) and climate engineering (large-scale deliberate interventions in the earth's climate system to diminish climate change or its impacts). According to GAO the United States lacks a clear strategy for climate engineering research in the context of the federal response to climate change. GAO highlights the need for a national strategic plan to adapt to a changing climate, including defined federal priorities. Links to GAO publications (High Risk issues) and to recommended websites (reducing emissions)

The Climate Action Tracker (CAT) is an independent scientific analysis produced by four research organisations tracking climate action and global efforts towards the globally agreed aim of holding warming below 2°C, since 2009. The CAT tracks 32 countries covering about 80% of global emissions and calculates global warming consequence and emissions gaps The website provides an up-to-date assessment of individual national pledges, targets, INDCs, and currently implemented policy to reduce their greenhouse gas emissions. It has the support of the Children’s Investment Fund Foundation and ClimateWorks

The Climate Investment Funds (CIF) is providing 63 developing and middle income countries with urgently needed resources to mitigate and manage the challenges of climate change and reduce their greenhouse gas emissions. Designed to mobilize resources for climate-smart development, the CIF is currently the largest source of concessional financing for the mitigation and adaptation investments of partner multilateral development banks (MDBs). The CIF allocates financing through four funding windows: the Clean Technology Fund (CTF) - The Forest Investment Program (FIP) – The Pilot Program for Climate Resilience (PPCR) – The Scaling Up Renewable Energy in Low Income Countries Program (SREP)
résumé : "Citizens’ Climate Lobby is a non-profit / non-partisan / grassroots advocacy organization focused on national policies to address climate change."

EL Draft : Personal point of view of a former physics professor. Articles present aspects of the "global warming social phenomenon and environmental, health and safety issues". The author does not consider the climate change as a threat and is against climate change alarmism.

In view of the recent climate disasters in the U.S., Climate Silence chronicle the “slow, collective descent toward mute acceptance of global calamity” with the objective to lay out “in painstaking detail just how far our national conversation has drifted from where it needs to be”, and provide “an opportunity for American voters concerned about the climate crisis to speak out and let the candidates know that they want the silence to end”. The sub-sections “Data” and “Graph” depict major statements about climate change, climate policy, and climate-related disasters by President Obama and Mitt Romney dating back to the 2008 presidential campaign; the statements are displayed on the graph according to categories : Action - Promise - Affirmation - Avoidance - Denial – Exacerbation (exacerbation dismisses climate change as a problem and advocates for a policy which will increase greenhouse gas emissions and make climate change worse)

Climate change page of the SEIA (Solar energy industries association). SEIA represent all organizations that promote, manufacture, install and support the development of solar energy, and works with 1000 member companies to promote the use of clean, affordable solar in America by expanding markets, removing market barriers, strengthening the industry and educating the public on the benefits of solar energy. SEIA participated in the 16th and 15th COP to highlight the role that solar energy can play in combating climate change: solar energy means “more jobs, more energy, and less CO2”. Considers that while there may be not be one technology that can reduce all U.S. ghg emissions to zero, solar technologies come close. List of climate links (Greenhouse gas reporting programs and data) and topic tags on solar energy

The Global Catholic Climate Movement For God’s creation, the poor and future generations is a community of thousands of Catholics and a global network of partners, responding to the Pope’s call to action in the Laudato Si’ encyclical and working together on the climate change crisis. Objectives are: To raise awareness within the Church about the urgency of climate action; To support global solidarity on the current ecological crisis; To promote ecological conversion through personal and organisational change to reduce emissions and transition to a low carbon world; To advance the Catholic relationship between faith and reason, especially as it relates to adaptive decision making in areas of climate change policy; To urge political, business and social leaders to commit to ambitious climate action to solve the crisis and keep the global temperature increase below 1.5 degree Celsius (relative to pre-industrial levels)

The Caribbean Community Climate Change Centre coordinates the Caribbean region’s response to climate change, working on solutions and projects to combat the environmental impacts of climate change and global warming. It provides climate change-related policy advice and guidelines to the Caribbean Community (CARICOM) Member States through the CARICOM Secretariat and to the UK Caribbean Overseas Territories and is archive and clearing house for regional climate change data and documentation. The Centre provides timely forecasts and analyses of potentially hazardous impacts of both natural and man-induced climatic changes on the environment, and the development of special programmes which create opportunities for sustainable development. The main goal is to improve the ability of Caribbean people living in communities at risk from climate change to adopt more sustainable lifestyles

The blog focuses on reconsidering the causes of climate change (natural causes vs causes related to human activities) ; among the topics discussed : Schoolroom climate change indoctrination. Global warming hysteria. The consistent wiew is that climate sensitivity to increased levels of CO2 is negligible.T he assumptions are made based on excerpted publications and communications by scientists

The overall aim of the International Partnership on Mitigation and MRV is to support a practical exchange on mitigation-related activities and MRV between developing and developed countries. The Partnership has no formal character and seeks to: foster mutual learning between peers - identify best practices - establish a shared mitigation-related knowledge base - disseminate lessons learnt. Several databases : good practices (http://mitigationpartnership.net/gpa) projects and initiatives working on LEDS, NAMAs and MRV (http://mitigationpartnership.net/map) resources and documents on mitigation-related topics. Links to other networks in the field (http://mitigationpartnership.net/links)

The Nongovernmental International Panel on Climate Change (NIPCC) is an international panel of nongovernment scientists and scholars who define themselves as not being predisposed to believe climate change is caused by human greenhouse gas emissions, and being able to look at evidence the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) ignores. Since September 1, 2014, summaries of new scientific research articles and other posting are to be found at the CO2 Science website, which is managed by the Center for the Study of Carbon Dioxide and Global Change, one of the three main supporting organizations of the NIPCC

Section Climate change of The Guardian dealing with issues related to climate change such as energy, climate, ecology, etc. The newspaper engaged a climate campaign with the COP21 Conference coming. The initiative of The Guardian "Keep it in the ground" asks two funds to divest from the 200 top fossil fuel companies within five years.
