Climate Action Network Canada – Réseau action climat Canada (CAN-Rac Canada) is a coalition of more than 100 organizations that cares about how a changing climate affects people, plants and wildlife. The member organizations are working together to advance solutions to managing carbon pollution through sustainable and equitable development. CAN-Rac Canada brings First Nations, Inuit and Metis, private sector, labour, and civil society together with the key national and provincial environmental organizations working on climate change, and is helping Canadian organizations understand and respond to climate change impacts and policies in Canada and around the world and to coordinate their collective work on this issue to maximize their collective impact. Maintains a Tar Sands Database

Climate CoLab is a project of the MIT center for collective intelligence. The goal is to harness the collective intelligence of people from all around the world to address global climate change. Inspired by systems like Wikipedia and Linux, the center has developed a crowdsourcing platform where citizens work with experts and each other to create, analyze, and select detailed proposals for what to do about climate change. Community members are invited to submit and comment on proposals outlining ideas for what they think should be done about climate change: specific kinds of actions (generating electric power with fewer emissions, changing social attitudes about climate change, integrated climate action plans for a country, a group of countries, or the whole world). The 2014 winning proposals included (a) instituting a US carbon tax that creates pro-growth tax reform while also protecting the poor and reducing the federal deficit, (b) better educating building technicians to take advantage of the often unused energy-saving potential of sophisticated heating and cooling systems, and (c) using radio programs and two-way text messaging to help residents of coastal areas in Tanzania (and other developing countries) adapt to changing weather and other effects of climate change

Contents are described as “Various musings on climate science and policy by Roger Pielke Jr”, a professor at the University of Colorado. The current post should be the last one on the blog, as RP is one of 7 US academics being investigated by the US House of Representatives Committee on Environment and Natural Resources, the investigators questioning RP repeated claim that it is “incorrect to associate the increasing costs of disasters with the emission of greenhouse gases.” RP, who says to have publicly supported Pdt Obama’s proposed EPA carbon regulations, denies to be a climate skeptic. Previous posts are assuming that : the economic impact of the floods in the US is diminishing ; the decarbonization of energy consumption will only decrease the world’s reliance on fossil fuels by a small amount ; no significant time-dependent trends can be detected in frequency of East Coast Winter Storms, etc…

The UN’s initiative for business leadership on Climate Change, was launched by UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon in July 2007. The initiative is jointly convened by the UNFCCC and the UNEP. Caring for Climate endeavors to help prevent a climate change crisis by mobilizing a critical mass of business leaders to implement and recommend climate change solutions and policies. Caring for Climate is endorsed by 403 organizations. Caring for Climate signatories are encouraged to be actively engaged and contribute to the initiative’s multiple issues and workstreams listed below : Business leadership on carbon pricing – Climate adaptation – Responsible corporate engagement on climate change policy – Climate and energy action hub- Transparency and disclosure

International organisation consisting of health professionals who recognise the urgent need to address climate change to protect health The CHC aims to: Articulate and amplify the message of the need to address environmental and climate issues to protect health ; Empower and connect health professionals to take action to reduce emissions at home and at work ; Consolidate the international health voice calling for effective governmental and inter-governmental action to protect health from environmental degradation and climate change. The Charter, signed by thousands of health professionals around the world, comprises 5 points : Climate change is an avoidable threat to health - Low-carbon societies are the next great health advance - Climate change is increasing the health differential between rich and poor - Health depends on sustainable development - Delay will be fatal
Personal points of view about climate change policies. Authors are academics specialized in environmental studies (energy, climate, policies).

Blog created by a PhD candidate in an Atmospheric Science program at the University of Albany, collaborating with members of NASA’s Goddard Institute for Space Studies. He’s currently working on the study of the behavior of tropical paleoclimate and the modeling of such behavior. He also retains interest in a number of problems directly related to Earth’s climate, and other planets, this extending to the problem of modern global warming. Links to websites critical of the denial of anthropogenic warming

The homepage provides data on U.S. climate: climate, temperature departure, and precipitation in Washington, DC; national 3-month temperature outlook (the “Seasonal Outlook”) from Climate Prediction Center/National Weather Service stations/NOAA; Seasonal forecasts. List of local and U.S/ Global climate data links: Washington DC climate data; Maryland/DC/Delaware Drought Watch; Virginia Drought Watch; Presidential Inauguration weather; U.S./Global Daily to Seasonal Temperatures; Average and Record Weather by City; Drought Monitor ; U.S. Streamflow Data; Precipitation Analysis; Current Year Summary. List of climate weblogs and climate tutorials, mainly academic

SEI (Stockholm Environment Institute) maintains a subsite on the theme : Reducing Climate Risk. SEI research on this theme intends to show the benefits of a low carbon future and describe how we get there through mitigating and adapting to climate change. The goal of the theme is to support the design, development and implementation of effective and equitable strategies for adaptation and mitigation in developing and developed countries, taking into account the broader challenges and policy objectives of sustainable human development. Several sub-themes: Adaptation and vulnerability - Climate policy and governance - Climate finance and carbon markets - Climate mitigation and bioenergy

Documents the UK Government’s policies re. Climate change adaptation. The official documents database is browsable by document type (Case study – Closed consultation – Document collection – Consultation- Consultation outcome), Organisation, People)

Climate change education initiative of the NCSE (National Center for Science Education). Insists that it is important for the science of climate change to be taught, both in formal and informal educational environments, in order for future citizens to be able to make scientifically informed decisions about the consequences of climate change ; it is important to understand - and be able to rebut - arguments about climate science, and to understand why people choose to attack such well-tested science. The subsection “Climate Change Denial” provides the essential tools, and also describes how climate change denial is already threatening the integrity of science education

Presents UK’s climatological data sets and related climate statistics produced by the UK’s National Climate Information Centre. Specific information on the way to address climate change are given in several tools: The “"Pathway 2050" work presents a framework through which to consider some of the choices and trade-offs we will have to make over the next forty years ; the Carbon Footprint: Interactive calculator is designed to enable us to calculate our own carbon footprint. These tools are complemented with presentation of significant climate datasets used in the studies of climate change

The GCCA is a network of more than 450 nonprofit organizations in more than 70 countries with a shared goal - a world safe from runaway climate change. GCCA calls for: Phase-out of fossil fuels and a just transition to clean, renewable energy; Protection of our communities and forests, oceans and water resources; Leaders to take immediate action to close the gap between current actions and investments and what’s needed to secure our future; Sufficient funding to support the communities suffering most from the impacts of climate change. The GCCA has three main strategic priorities: Support partners to engage more people in taking action on climate change; amplifying the mobilisation efforts of the partner network to demonstrate growing public concern and support for change ; Positioning globally relevant climate campaigns at the top of the political agenda in selected countries, and work with partners to secure major changes over time

The title of the blog is from a quote by the statistician George E. P. Box: “essentially, all models are wrong, but some are useful”. The author is a climate modeller at the University of Bristol. His research is in using models of the earth system - climate, ice sheets, and vegetation - to recreate the past and predict the future, and in trying to quantify the inevitable uncertainties. Takes the view that all models are undoubtedly ‘wrong’, because we cannot precisely simulate every breath of wind, every raindrop, or every worm turning over the soil, but this does not preclude their usefulness as tools to explore the broad consequences of known physical laws. Discusses how to quantify uncertainties in modelling climate change and its impacts, past and future, and how to assess the usefulness of a climate model

Run by the Belmopan, the Belize-based Caribbean Community Climate Change Centre (CCCCC). Provides information about the center (news, actions, initiatives) some tips and some news about climate change in the caribbean area.

The Climate Code Foundation is a non-profit organisation founded in August 2010, to promote the public understanding of climate science. We work with climate scientists, science communicators, open knowledge experts, funding bodies, institutions, and governmental and inter-governmental agencies to improve software practices in climate science and to encourage the publication of climate science software.

Climate Change page on the website of the SHELL Oil Company. Asserts that to manage CO2, governments and industry must work together. Shell is in support of an international framework that puts a price on CO2, encouraging the use of all CO2-reducing technologies. Shell is taking action across four areas to help secure a sustainable energy future : natural gas, biofuels, carbon capture and storage, and energy efficiency

Draft EL (cellule draft bloquée) : The Climate Registry "designs and operates voluntary and compliance GHG reporting programs globally". It helps its members to measure and report the GHG. The website presents the programs, the tools available and the list of the members.

Stop Climate Chaos Scotland (SCCS) is a diverse coalition of organisations in Scotland campaigning together on climate change.  Our members include environment, faith and international development organisations, trade and student unions and community groups.

The GEF (Global environment facility) is an operating entity of the financial mechanism of the UNFCCC. GEF projects in climate change help developing countries and economies in transition to contribute to the overall objective of the UNFCCC. The GEF supports projects in Climate Change Mitigation: Reducing or avoiding greenhouse gas emissions in the areas of renewable energy; energy efficiency; sustainable transport; and management of land use, land-use change ,and forestry (LULUCF) and projects in Climate Change Adaptation

The World Meteorological Organization (WMO) is a specialized agency of the UN. Under WMO leadership National Meteorological and Hydrological Services contribute to the protection of life and property against natural disasters, to safeguarding the environment and to enhancing economic and social well-being in areas such as food security, water resources and transport. WMO promotes cooperation in the establishment of networks for making meteorological, climatological, hydrological and geophysical observations, as well as the exchange, processing and standardization of related data. It furthers the application of meteorology to the mitigation of the impacts of natural disasters

The website "gets skeptical about global warming skepticism", and is advocating that scientists should challenge themselves to improve their understanding. Collects, criticizes and analyses the peer reviewed scientific literature with the purpose of deconstrucing the climate myths and fighting climate change denial

Personal points of view edited by Patrick Whittle (completing a PhD in political philosophy at the University of Canterbury in New Zealand) and Douglas Campbell (PhD in philosophy from the University of Arizona). Aimed to "fairly presenting both sides of the issue".

A personal point of view from Ole Humlum whose objective is to "provide information on meteorological and climatologically issues of general and specific to assist reflective people to form a personal opinion"

The Climate Reality Project is a diverse group of passionate individuals who have come together to help solve the greatest challenge of our time. We are cultural leaders, marketers, organizers, scientists, storytellers and more, and we are committed to building a better future together.

Environment news section of the Guardian, with a sub-section on climate change. Among recent postings, an interview of Naomi Klein on climate change (I thought it best to write about my own raw terror) published on the 26th August 2015
A blog highlighting the "ill-founded political campaign around the threat of CAGW. A campaign which is irresponsible, destructive, divisive, and degrading."

Anonymous blog. "I am not a climate scientist, but a professional and active scientist who teaches and carries out research at a university". The blog aims to bring a critical eye on the scientific debate to highlight the anthropogenic nature of global warming.
A personal point of view. Sea Surface Temperature, Ocean Heat Content, and Other Climate Change Discussions. Highlights "The unquestioning belief in catastrophic human-induced climate change ..."

National Snow & Ice Data Center manages cryosphere-related data ranging from text files to remote sensing data from NASA’s Earth Observing System satellite program. Specialises in remote sensing of snow and ice, Arctic climate, frozen ground, ice sheets, glaciers etc. Works with data providers and users.
Website of the Stop Global Warming Virtual March a non-political movement to demand world leaders freeze and reduce carbon dioxide emissions now.

“10:10 is about doing “practical stuff that helps solve climate change”. From riding a bus to repowering a village with solar energy, the projects “bring people together to help build a better world” ; focus is on renewables powered projects in France, UK, The Netherlands, Germany…"

A personal blog by B. Tisdale. He previously believed in the assumption that man is responsible for most of the recent global warming. He is dissatisfied with the ever increasing number of reports of projected climate catastrophes. He understand the hypothesis of anthropogenic greenhouse gas-driven global warming, and still believe it has an impact on the warming of land surfaces, albeit a small one.

The U.S. Government Accountability Office (GAO) is an independent agency that works for Congress, often called the "congressional watchdog.” The GAO investigates Federal Government expenses. According to the GAO the United States lacks a clear strategy for climate engineering research in the context of the federal response to climate change. GAO highlights the need for a national strategic plan to adapt to a changing climate, including defined federal priorities.

Contents are described as “Various musings on climate science and policy by Roger Pielke Jr”, a professor at the University of Colorado. “Climatology based on science instead of political and social agendas. “The Climate Busters!” posts data and research dealing with all aspects of climatology and exposes the myth of anthropogenic global warming.”

WRI is a global research organization spanning more than 50 countries. Our more than 450 experts and staff work closely with leaders to turn big ideas into action. Work focuses on six critical issues: climate, energy, food, forests, water, and cities and transport.

“NOAA Climate.gov provides science and information for a climate-smart nation. Americans’ health, security, and economic well-being are closely linked to climate and weather. People want and need information to help them make decisions on how to manage climate-related risks and opportunities they face.”
A personal point of view by Jennifer Marohasy BSc PhD "working on temperature reconstructions or a new experimental technique for long-range weather forecasting using artificial intelligence"

Climate Change Dispatch (CCD) considers environmentalism to be a church. Created with the explicit purpose to fighting the global warming alarmists ; includes links a voluntary group of people concerned about the extent to which carbon is wrongly vilified in Western societies

Conceived in 2010, to address the five major concerns that global warming sceptics had identified and plan further scientific investigations, a major education and communications program, and work to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in the places that will be the worst emitters over the next 30 years. Aims to forge a new coalition between industry and environmental groups for the use of cleanly-produced natural gas to slow global warming over the next few decades - focussing on China.

NIPCC is an international panel of nongovernment scientists and scholars. It is not a government agency, and because its members are not predisposed to believe climate change is caused by human greenhouse gas emissions, NIPCC is offers an independent “second opinion” of global warming evidence.

A personal point of view. "Presently my major muses are the behaviour of the stock markets, the mass hysteria that is the Global Warming panic, and metrology – or how we measure things both present and past. There will be some political commentary. I hope also that there will be some learning."

Supports decision-makers in designing and delivering climate compatible development, managed by an alliance of organisations led by PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP (PwC). Currently funded over seven-year period from March 2010 to April 2017 by the UK Department for International Development (DfID) and the Dutch Ministry of Foreign Affairs (DGIS).

Claims to "expose the truth about the Man-Made Climate Change theory". A collection of excerpts and quotations denouncing the environmental policies of the Carter and Obama administrations, as well as the action of warmists, greenies, leftists, and others. Warmism and Greenism are likened to a new form of religious fanaticism.

“The annual World Energy Outlook (WEO) is now the world’s most authoritative source of energy market analysis and projections, providing critical analytical insights into trends in energy demand and supply and what they mean for energy security, environmental protection and economic development. WEO projections are used by the public and private sector as a framework on which they can base their policy-making, planning and investment decisions and to identify what needs to be done to arrive at a supportable and sustainable energy future.”

Blog of Matt Ridley who writes a weekly column in The Times and writes regularly for the Wall Street Journal. As Viscount Ridley, he was elected to the House of Lords in February 2013. He is a fellow of the Royal Society of Literature and of the Academy of Medical Sciences. Matt Ridley's books have sold over a million copies. Most of his posts discus “the benefits of carbon dioxide” or the fact "Some Policies to Fight Climate Change Have Done More Harm Than Good”.

A personal point of view explaining that "there is good scientific evidence that human activities are influencing the climate. But evidence is not fact, and neither evidence nor fact speak for themselves..."

A worldwide network of over 900 Non-Governmental Organizations (NGOs) in more than 100 countries, working to promote government and individual action to limit human-induced climate change to ecologically sustainable levels.

Site devoted to the activities of Al Gore, president of the "Climate Reality Project", a non-profit organization with a social objective finding solutions to the "climate crisis." The project, initially called the "Alliance for Climate Protection" aims to raise awareness of the reality of the climate crisis and the dangers currently posed by pollution linked to global warming and possible solutions. It does this through interventions at the local level, in the media and on the internet.

“Founded in 1971 by economist Barbara Ward, who forged the concept and cause of sustainable development, International Institute for Environment and Development (IIED) advises government, business and development agencies, arguing for changes in public policy. IIED carries out research, advice and advocacy work, focusing on bottom-up solutions, informed by practical perspective acquired through hands-on research with grassroots partners… “

Global Landscapes Forums create a platform for stakeholders to identify policy options etc. by understanding how land-use choices affect different areas - negotiation of competing demands - assessing factors that affect land use - studying how groups benefit differently from land uses - leveraging private and public capital for sustainable development in the landscape.

PBL Netherlands Environmental Assessment Agency. Core tasks are: to investigate and document current environmental, ecological and spatial quality and to evaluate policy; to explore future social trends and possible policy options; to identify social issues of importance and identify possible strategic options for achieving government objectives in the field.

Headquartered in London, UK, Climate Action works in a unique, contractual partnership with the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP). For our partners and supporters we help engage the private sector ... for our clients we help generate profitable business opportunities and partnerships.

The American Meteorological Society promotes the development and dissemination of information and education on the atmospheric and related oceanic and hydrologic sciences and the advancement of their professional applications. AMS publishes eleven atmospheric and related oceanic and hydrologic journals — in print and online — sponsors more than 12 conferences annually, and offers numerous programs and services.

“The ECOFYS group, (H.O. Utrecht, Netherlands) specializes in expertise in energy saving, sustainable energy solutions and climate policies, with the purpose to help countries in designing policies in such a way that they bring economic benefits and reduced risks, to help opinion leaders develop new ideas for policy designs, and to help companies operate profitably in the policy landscape.”

Center for Clean Air Policy recognized expert since 1985 in climate and air quality policy as an " independent, nonprofit think tank working exclusively on those issues at the local, U.S. national and international levels."

A personal point of view explaining that there is "no significant cause-and-effect from CO2 on the global surface temperature, i.e. on climate. The global temperature was decreasing from 1940 to 1975."

The Green Climate Fund contributes to the achievement of the ultimate objective of the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) providing support to developing countries to limit or reduce their greenhouse gas emissions and to adapt to the impacts of climate change. It pursues a country-driven approach and promotes involvement of relevant institutions and stakeholders in order to maximize the impact of its funding for adaptation and mitigation.

Website of WWF’s Earth Hour, considered to be the world’s largest grassroots movement. Web pages dedicated to the celebration of the Earth Hour around the world, list of environmental projects with the purpose of working for a living planet and sustainable living etc.

Climatism aims to draw attention to the "alarmism" and the lack of reliable arguments against it. Anonymous points of view to challenge the "alarmists" (Gore, Viner, Hansen) claims and the "human induced climate change narrative".

Authors intend to expose “the truth about global warming hysteria”, and to oppose the alarmist agenda employed by most global warming “evangelists”, as based upon questionable scientific data and erroneous claims about global climate change. Readers are invited to “learn the truth” (list of “Must-see videos”) and then become actively involved in promoting “the cause of freedom” (“The ten things you can do”, including distribute GSM flyers, visit congressmen, write to papers, put GSM bumper sticker on car, make donations…)

Science and public policy institute (SPPI) claimed mission is to provide research and educational materials dedicated to sound public policy based on sound science, and support the advancement of sensible public policies rooted in rational science and economics. Links to several sceptical websites. Articles include: 35 Inconvenient Truths: The errors in Al Gore’s movie - Proved: There is No Climate Crisis - Fallacies about Global Warming.

Focus on President Obama’s America’s Clean Power Plan, standards are designed to reduce carbon dioxide emissions by 32 percent from 2005 levels by 2030. The Plan intends to: Protect the health of American families, boost the economy by leading to 30 percent more renewable energy generation in 2030, save enough energy to power 30 million homes in 2030 and save consumers $155 billion from 2020-2030.

A news and analysis website focused on providing the latest updates and insight into global low carbon developments. Funded by sponsors and web advertising. Founded by James Ramsey in 2002 to raise awareness about climate change. Official observer to various UN organisations. Expertise lies in facilitating public sector private sector partnerships having a working knowledge of current events in the climate change debate.

The Center for the Study of Carbon Dioxide and Global Change was created to disseminate factual reports and commentary on new developments in the world-wide scientific quest to determine the climatic and biological consequences of the ongoing rise in the air's CO2 content. Weekly online CO2 Science magazine. On-line instructions on how to conduct CO2 enrichment and depletion experiments. Specific projects and data: Medieval warm project period – Plants growth database – Ocean acidification database – World temperatures dataset
A personal point of view: PhD in High Energy Physics "interested in understanding the physics behind climate change after getting fed up with being told that the debate is over. "

“The Institute for Energy Research (IER) is a not-for-profit organization that conducts intensive research and analysis on the functions, operations, and government regulation of global energy markets. IER maintains that freely-functioning energy markets provide the most efficient and effective solutions to today’s global energy and environmental challenges and, as such, are critical to the well-being of individuals and society… Founded in 1989 the IER is a public foundation under the Internal Revenue Code and is funded entirely by tax deductible contributions from individuals, foundations and corporations.

CFACT was founded to promote a positive voice on environment and development issues, with the ultimate goal to enhance the fruitfulness of the earth and all of its inhabitants. Links to Climatehustle.org, a website intending to show how global warming has become a new religion for alarmists.

Blog of the Canadian investigative journalist Donna Laframboise. Argues that The IPCC is an "unprofessional, scandal-plagued organization, led by people with low standards and impaired judgment, and that we need to stop taking it seriously".

Climate realists aims to draw attention to its view of the real explanations as to what has made the climate change and to voice an educated opinion against the “unscientific and unsubstantiated reasoning” behind green taxation. Promotes the proposition that there is no such thing as Man Made Climate Change.
United States Environmental Protection Agency. EPA's purpose is to ensure that all Americans are protected from significant risks to human health and the environment where they live, learn and work.

“World Climate Report, a concise, hard-hitting and scientifically correct response to the global change reports which gain attention in the literature and popular press. As the nation’s leading publication in this realm, World Climate Report is exhaustively researched, impeccably referenced, and always timely. This popular web log points out the weaknesses and outright fallacies in the science that is being touted as “proof” of disastrous warming. It’s the perfect antidote against those who argue for proposed changes to the Rio Climate Treaty, such as the Kyoto Protocol, which are aimed at limiting carbon emissions from the United States.”

A personal point of view "The elevation of the hockey stick and the whole global warming thing to iconic status makes it a giant with feet of clay – poorly founded and ready to crumble. Time to do some digging…"

Photographic documentation of climate change, by Gary Braasch. The website was designed to “make the climate change visible”, Subject matters: Antarctica – Arctic – Alaska – Unstable weather – Glaciers – Coastlines/Sea levels – Oceans and Tropics – Hawaii – Himalaya and Asia – South America – World Climate change.
An independent organization of leading scientists and journalists researching and reporting the facts about changing climate and its impact on the American public.

GWIR was founded in 2006 by Tom Schueneman, member of the Society of environmental journalists. In addition to publishing GlobalWarmingisReal, Tom is also the founder of TDS Environmental Media, which includes HippieMagazine and TheGreenWashingBlog. A contributing writer for several environmental blogs, including TriplePundit, Slate, Cleantechnica, Planetsave, Earth911 and others.

Observations of anthropogenic global warming (by Ari Jokimäki). Blog designed to offer relevant information. Main categories: Adaptation & Mitigation - AGW evidence - Climate claims - Climate science - Global warming effects. Articles republished on Skeptical Science - RealClimate

The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) was established by the United Nations Environmental Programme (UNEP) and the World Meteorological Organization (WMO) in 1988. Three working groups: WGI: The Science of Climate Change - WGII: Impacts, Adaptation and Vulnerability - WGIII:Mitigation of Climate Change, and a Task Force on Greenhouse Gas Inventories. IPPC prepares comprehensive Assessment Reports at regular intervals.

The blog is “about the insanity surrounding Anthropogenic Global Warming". Categories include: Eco Jihad - Ecoterror - Climate Alarmism - Climategate, Climategate 2, Climategate 2.0 - Plumegate - Seefoodgate. On the blogroll : Global Warming Science - Climate Depot - What Really Happened - Tory Ardvark - Watts Up With That? etc

The mission of “Climate Busters”, hosted by SouthWest Weather Inc., favours a particular solar climate mechanism/connection theory according to which they ”expect global cooling to be quite substantial going forward”

The World Meteorological Organization (WMO) is a specialized agency of the UN contributing to the protection of life and property against natural disasters, to safeguarding the environment and to enhancing economic and social well-being in areas such as food security, water resources and transport. WMO promotes cooperation in the establishment of networks for making meteorological, climatological, hydrological and geophysical observations, as well as the exchange, processing and standardization of related data. It furthers the application of meteorology to the mitigation of the impacts of natural disasters

The European Climate Foundation (ECF) as a philanthropic initiative since 2008 promotes climate and energy policies to reduce Europe’s greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions and works to bring European political actors to have a stronger action in mitigating climate change.   It carries out a multifaceted strategy with sectoral programmes, cross-cutting initiatives, and geographic initiatives, and supports transition to a low-carbon economy.   It adresses the lack of general public awareness about the consequences of climate change with publications, events and analysis bor a better understanding.

Climate Access defines itself as “The network for those engaging the public in the transformation to low-carbon, resilient communities”. The “ResourceHub” is a collection of resources for essential research, news articles and commentary on climate change communications, behavior change and public opinion). The “CampaignGallery” is shows how individuals, communities and organizations are taking action to address climate change.

“Climate Analytics is a non-­profit organisation based in Berlin, Germany that has been established to synthesise climate science and policy research that is relevant for international climate policy negotiations. Our main aim is to provide scientific, policy and analytical support for Small Island Developing States (SIDS) and the least developed country (LDCs) negotiators, as well as non-governmental organisations and other stakeholders in the international climate negotiations.”

The UNDP and the World Bank Group have developed a web-based knowledge platform, which a number of UN agencies and multilateral development banks (MDBs) use. The platform provides a harmonised description of types of funds available, examples of successful cases of blending different types of grant and concessional funds to leverage private sector financing, knowledge centre with a glossary of terminology, a library , and tools to enable project developers to analyse their own projects for better-informed decisions.

Group of private citizens, comprised mainly of active and retired earth and atmospheric scientists, geologists, geophysicists, engineers and other professionals, who are concerned about the apparent gross manipulation and falsification of scientific data to convince authorities that a problem exists, and the one-sided misinformation being fed to children in school, especially the Al Gore movie, which has been shown to contain a large number of false claims.

Climateworks is a team of researchers, strategists, collaborators, and grant-makers, with the goal of increasing philanthropic impact on climate change. Strategies defined in 2007 in the joint publication: Design to Win: Philanthropy’s Role in the Fight Against Global Warming, a report that identified priorities charted course for climate philanthropy. The Hewlett, Packard, and McKnight foundations — created ClimateWorks in 2008. In 2013 CW took on a bigger role to help leading climate funders coordinate and to work with partners around the world to grow climate philanthropy and reduce the emissions. CV supports maximizing the energy that comes from sustainable, affordable, low-carbon sources, putting an emphasis on effective public policy, business innovation, public support.

The goal of the ICTSD, founded in 1996 in Geneva, is to advance sustainable development through trade related policy-making, through 3 types of activities: 1.: Information and communication 2: Policy dialogue (to create opportunities for dialogue and facilitate constructive interaction among policymakers and influencers in non-negotiating settings) - 3: Research and analysis. The Climate and energy subsection is dedicated to promoting the transition to a low carbon economy and a sustainable energy future.

CARE climate change information centre. CARE has developed several global learning, research, and advocacy programmes, and Practitioner's tools designed to help humanitarian and development practitioners integrate climate change risk management into their projects; Climate change advocacy toolkits, Community based adaptation (CBA) project toolkit, the CVCA handbook (Climate vulnerability and capacity assessment) which is CARE's most popular practitioner's tool, and the Gender and inclusion tool

We are sheep and beef farmers farming off the East Coast of the North Island of NZ. We believe all decisions should be based on scientific fact, not mere conjecture. Our aim is to counter the misinformation being presented in the general media about imminent catastrophe caused by man-made global warming, to raise awareness of the political manoeuvrings regarding climate change and the Emissions Trading Scheme in New Zealand
Personal points of view edited by Marc Morano, senior aide, speechwriter, and climate researcher for Senator James Inhofe (Republican-OK).

“The Least Developed Countries are 48 nations that are especially vulnerable to climate change but have done the least to cause the problem. They work together at the intergovernmental negotiations under the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change with two aims. First, to demand that wealthier nations act in accordance with their responsibility for creating the problem and their capability for addressing it. Second, to play a leadership role in global efforts to prevent dangerous climate change.”

Introduction to the UNEP (United Nations Environment Program) website on climate change. Insists that the most dangerous climate changes may still be avoided if we transform our hydrocarbon based energy systems and if we initiate rational and adequately financed adaptation programmes to forestall disasters and migrations at unprecedented scales.
Blog by Tom Nelson (Masters of Science degree in Electrical and Electronics Engineering). “CO2 is not the climate control knob”.

A personal point of view by Carl Wolk "I am a freshman student at ... and I also run the blog Climate Change Clarity. I have no future aspirations in climate science besides continuing to do the work I’m doing now." and Erl Happ "I am a winemaker and grape-grower with a strong interest in climate ..."

DC was formed in 2007 with two core purposes: to syndicate quality journalism about climate change to other media outlets, and to provide a daily aggregation highlighting the best news on climate change from around the globe. The Daily Climate's aggregation represents the news of the day, irrespective of the opinion or viewpoint expressed, or whether or not material in the article is consistent with their understanding of current science.

“The Copenhagen Consensus Center is a think tank is advising policy-makers and philanthropists how to spend their money most effectively on solving “the world biggest problems”. Conceived to address a fundamental, but overlooked topic in international development: In a world with limited budgets and attention spans, we need to find effective ways to do the most good for the most people. Among current projects, the Fix The Climate project, based on the consideration that Global warming is caused by man-made CO2 emissions, and we need to do something about it.”

Personnal point of view on Global warming as an hysterical alarm built on exaggeration and deceit, fuelled by those with a vested interest. The author gives arguments against the "warmists" and is actively involved in various campaigns: to support the US governors who defy Obama climate rule - to support scrapping the Climate Change Act - to oppose Emission Trading - to endorse the Manhattan declaration on Climate Change (Climate Change is not a global crisis) - to try to keep Al Gore's "political propaganda film" out of English schools, etc
A personal point of view about the "anti-science political agenda that is driving governments to fabricate excess global warming that really does not exist."

350.org was founded by a group of university friends in the U.S.and Bill McKibben, who wrote one of the first books on global warming for the general public. The number 350 means reducing the amount of CO2 in the atmosphere from its current level of 400 parts per million to below 350 ppm. Climate-focused campaigns, projects and actions are led from the bottom-up by people in 188 countries using Email to connect with each other.

The InterAcademy Council (IAC) is a multinational organization of science academies created to produce reports on scientific, technological, and health issues related challenges such as enhancing global surveillance of emerging infectious diseases, improving global water quality and availability, and scientific ethics and responsibilities. Provides knowledge and advice to national governments and international organizations.

Website of the transformational Climate Science conference, hosted by the University of Exeter in partnership with the Met Office and University of Leeds on 15 and 16 May, 2015. Climate change experts critically reflected on the IPCC’s Fifth Assessment Report (AR5). The report assesses scientific, technical, and socio-economic factors concerning climate change, its potential effects and the options for adaptation and mitigation.

This Greenpeace project compiles Exxon Foundation funding to a series of institutions who have worked to undermine solutions to global warming and climate change in recent years. Individuals working with these organizations and their global warming quotes and deeds are detailed. There are downloadable source documents or links to sources are provided throughout.

Carbon Brief reports on the latest developments and media coverage of climate science and energy policy, with a particular focus on the UK. News coverage, analysis and factchecks, they publish a daily and weekly email briefing.

The goal is to harness the collective intelligence of people from all around the world to address global climate change. Inspired by systems like Wikipedia and Linux, the center has developed a crowdsourcing platform where citizens work with experts and each other to create, analyze, and select detailed proposals for what to do about climate change.
